WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:18.070 --> 00:00:21.070
MICHAEL BRENNER: Welcome to the
second lecture in our series

00:00:21.070 --> 00:00:26.050
on Science and Cooking, and we're
delighted today to have Joanne Chang.

00:00:26.050 --> 00:00:27.800
This week the topic
is phase transitions.

00:00:27.800 --> 00:00:29.350
Now phase transitions is
what happens, like when

00:00:29.350 --> 00:00:31.670
you boil water-- you know
that when you heat water,

00:00:31.670 --> 00:00:34.580
it goes from being a normal
temperature, to being at some point

00:00:34.580 --> 00:00:38.379
the liquid transforms
to a gas-- and there are

00:00:38.379 --> 00:00:39.920
lots of phase transitions in cooking.

00:00:39.920 --> 00:00:42.400
I mean, in fact, arguably
cooking is really

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:44.110
the control of phase transitions.

00:00:44.110 --> 00:00:47.950
And it turns out that one of the
most useful phase transitions,

00:00:47.950 --> 00:00:51.260
and really one of the most interesting
for cooking, happens with sugar water.

00:00:51.260 --> 00:00:55.410
Which is going to play, I think, a
prominent role in tonight's lecture.

00:00:55.410 --> 00:00:59.980
And I mean the thing about sugar water--
actually is anyone drinking Coca Cola?

00:00:59.980 --> 00:01:01.616
Does anyone have a Coca Cola?

00:01:01.616 --> 00:01:02.490
You have a Coca Cola?

00:01:02.490 --> 00:01:03.770
No one will admit it?

00:01:03.770 --> 00:01:05.830
So I mean, OK, so let
me ask you a question.

00:01:05.830 --> 00:01:07.340
In fact, maybe in fact I'm
not going to use my slides,

00:01:07.340 --> 00:01:09.710
maybe I'm going to talk about
phase transitions instead.

00:01:09.710 --> 00:01:11.780
So I should have brought this demo.

00:01:11.780 --> 00:01:15.167
So does anybody know if we
took-- is that a beaker of water?

00:01:15.167 --> 00:01:16.250
JOANNE CHANG: This is ice.

00:01:16.250 --> 00:01:16.720
MICHAEL BRENNER: That's ice.

00:01:16.720 --> 00:01:19.240
So if we took water, that's
about how much water is that?

00:01:19.240 --> 00:01:22.040
That's about-- that's 5
and 1/2 cups of water.

00:01:22.040 --> 00:01:26.687
Does anybody know how much sugar we can
dissolve in 5 and 1/2 cups of water?

00:01:26.687 --> 00:01:29.020
That is for example, suppose
we had another beaker which

00:01:29.020 --> 00:01:31.460
is filled with sugar up
to this level, do you

00:01:31.460 --> 00:01:34.180
think if we mixed it in the
water it would dissolve?

00:01:34.180 --> 00:01:35.590
Who votes yes?

00:01:35.590 --> 00:01:37.230
Who votes no?

00:01:37.230 --> 00:01:40.085
OK, so most of you didn't vote.

00:01:40.085 --> 00:01:41.072
Did you notice that?

00:01:41.072 --> 00:01:41.780
They didn't vote.

00:01:41.780 --> 00:01:44.250
So let's try it again, you're not
allowed to get away with that.

00:01:44.250 --> 00:01:47.124
So this is a straightforward question,
you can go home and verify it.

00:01:47.124 --> 00:01:50.620
If we had 5 and 1/2 cups
of sugar, and we poured it

00:01:50.620 --> 00:01:54.550
in 5 and 1/2 cups of water, who
votes that it would dissolve?

00:01:54.550 --> 00:01:56.860
Who votes that it wouldn't dissolve?

00:01:56.860 --> 00:02:00.760
OK, so what if we have
5 and 1/2 cups of salt?

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:02.610
Instead of sugar, salt.

00:02:02.610 --> 00:02:04.000
It's a cooking material right?

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:06.520
You can use salt?

00:02:06.520 --> 00:02:08.550
Who thinks that the salt would dissolve?

00:02:08.550 --> 00:02:11.170
Who thinks that the
salt would not dissolve?

00:02:11.170 --> 00:02:13.994
OK, so what if we had 10 cups of sugar?

00:02:13.994 --> 00:02:15.410
So that's 5 and 1/2 cups of water.

00:02:15.410 --> 00:02:17.350
Suppose I had 10 cups of sugar?

00:02:17.350 --> 00:02:19.120
Who thinks it would dissolve?

00:02:19.120 --> 00:02:20.766
Who thinks it wouldn't dissolve?

00:02:20.766 --> 00:02:22.140
OK, you're getting better voting.

00:02:22.140 --> 00:02:26.470
So the answer is that 10
cups of sugar would dissolve.

00:02:26.470 --> 00:02:31.190
So the solubility-- So you can
dissolve twice the weight of sugar

00:02:31.190 --> 00:02:33.800
in the equivalent weight of
water at room temperature.

00:02:33.800 --> 00:02:36.350
Now Joanne's going to be doing a lot of
boiling, are you going to be boiling?

00:02:36.350 --> 00:02:36.950
JOANNE CHANG: I am, yeah.

00:02:36.950 --> 00:02:38.700
MICHAEL BRENNER: So
when you boil, suppose

00:02:38.700 --> 00:02:40.970
you have water at 100 degrees
Celsius, boiling point.

00:02:43.469 --> 00:02:45.010
How much sugar can you dissolve then?

00:02:45.010 --> 00:02:45.810
Does anybody know?

00:02:45.810 --> 00:02:46.934
Maybe I'll ask it this way.

00:02:46.934 --> 00:02:50.130
So let's say we had 11-- so
I'm leading you to the answer--

00:02:50.130 --> 00:02:51.890
but we said 11 cups.

00:02:51.890 --> 00:02:53.000
So what about 15 cups?

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:55.630
Can you, at boiling water, 15 cups?

00:02:55.630 --> 00:02:56.560
20 cups?

00:02:56.560 --> 00:02:57.510
Who votes 15?

00:02:57.510 --> 00:02:58.720
Who says yes?

00:02:58.720 --> 00:02:59.330
20?

00:02:59.330 --> 00:03:00.360
Who says yes?

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:03.920
So it turns out four times, it's a
factor of 4 at 100 degrees Celsius.

00:03:03.920 --> 00:03:07.250
It's also the case-- and maybe this is
a better intro than what I've prepared,

00:03:07.250 --> 00:03:08.560
come to think of it,
cause this might even

00:03:08.560 --> 00:03:10.750
be relevant for what
you're going to talk about,

00:03:10.750 --> 00:03:14.610
that's unusual right-- so it's
also the case that-- I don't

00:03:14.610 --> 00:03:18.200
know if you knew this, but-- the
boiling point of sugar water mixtures

00:03:18.200 --> 00:03:20.140
increases with temperature.

00:03:20.140 --> 00:03:25.860
So if you actually were to put four
cups of sugar into a cup of water

00:03:25.860 --> 00:03:28.137
at 100 degrees Celsius, the
water wouldn't be boiling,

00:03:28.137 --> 00:03:30.970
the mixture wouldn't be boiling,
the boiling point actually goes up.

00:03:30.970 --> 00:03:33.730
And I think what you're going to
see when Joanne gives this lecture,

00:03:33.730 --> 00:03:35.000
and this is dangerous
for me to see, cause

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:37.124
I have absolutely no idea
what you're going to say,

00:03:37.124 --> 00:03:39.432
but anyway this will
be-- except that she's

00:03:39.432 --> 00:03:42.700
going to talk about sugar-- is that
you have to control temperature

00:03:42.700 --> 00:03:43.370
very carefully.

00:03:43.370 --> 00:03:47.865
Because what happens, of course,
is that if you just dump heat in it

00:03:47.865 --> 00:03:51.010
then the thing starts to boil, the
gas comes off, and that of course

00:03:51.010 --> 00:03:53.580
means that the sugar fraction increases.

00:03:53.580 --> 00:03:56.120
Which makes the boiling
point increase more,

00:03:56.120 --> 00:03:58.940
which makes the sugar
fraction increase even more,

00:03:58.940 --> 00:04:00.660
and there's a runaway
phenomenon in this.

00:04:00.660 --> 00:04:03.800
Which is the reason, how
many of you make candy?

00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:05.679
How many of you don't make candy?

00:04:05.679 --> 00:04:06.720
Okay good, just checking.

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:10.492
Which is the reason that you
have to buy candy thermometers.

00:04:10.492 --> 00:04:12.450
Joanne I don't think
needs a candy thermometer.

00:04:15.834 --> 00:04:18.500
So she'll explain to you how she
gets away with this presumably.

00:04:18.500 --> 00:04:19.970
Or she doesn't, ask her.

00:04:19.970 --> 00:04:22.226
So with no further ado,
let me introduce Joanne.

00:04:22.226 --> 00:04:24.100
So I actually-- it always
makes me very happy

00:04:24.100 --> 00:04:26.349
to introduce Joanne for a
number of different reasons,

00:04:26.349 --> 00:04:30.270
but one of them-- which for those of you
have come here before, you've heard me

00:04:30.270 --> 00:04:33.280
say this but I'll just say it
again-- is that Joanne was a Harvard

00:04:33.280 --> 00:04:36.490
undergraduate, and she
was an applied math major.

00:04:36.490 --> 00:04:40.960
And I, as it happens, run the
applied math major at Harvard.

00:04:40.960 --> 00:04:46.110
And I've never understood why I was
involved in the science of cooking.

00:04:46.110 --> 00:04:50.060
And Joanne though, well
she was in applied math,

00:04:50.060 --> 00:04:51.740
and she actually knows what she's doing.

00:04:51.740 --> 00:04:55.450
And so it's sort of
somehow made me feel good.

00:04:55.450 --> 00:04:58.064
So anyway with that, Joanne, thank you.

00:04:58.064 --> 00:05:00.320
JOANNE CHANG: Thank you.

00:05:00.320 --> 00:05:02.020
Thank you, for that introduction.

00:05:02.020 --> 00:05:06.290
I always learn something from the
introduction that you give, Michael.

00:05:06.290 --> 00:05:07.880
You always explain stuff.

00:05:07.880 --> 00:05:11.630
So one of the reasons why I
love coming to these classes,

00:05:11.630 --> 00:05:15.410
I'm a nervous wreck the entire
week before, I still am right now,

00:05:15.410 --> 00:05:18.930
but in that quick 5 or 10
minutes that Michael speaks,

00:05:18.930 --> 00:05:21.850
I always learn a little bit
more about what it is that I do.

00:05:21.850 --> 00:05:25.830
Because I know how it works, and
I can explain what will happen,

00:05:25.830 --> 00:05:28.840
but I didn't even think about what
was happening with the boiling point.

00:05:28.840 --> 00:05:31.230
We are going to boil sugar,
I'm going to show you

00:05:31.230 --> 00:05:34.080
different things you can do with
the different stages of sugar.

00:05:34.080 --> 00:05:38.180
But I didn't even think about
the actual boiling point rising.

00:05:38.180 --> 00:05:39.930
A little bit into the
lecture, I will talk

00:05:39.930 --> 00:05:44.750
about the freezing point of a liquid,
and how when you add sugar to it

00:05:44.750 --> 00:05:46.410
actually depresses the freezing point.

00:05:46.410 --> 00:05:48.660
But I hadn't thought about
how it works the other way.

00:05:48.660 --> 00:05:50.850
So that was really fun to learn.

00:05:50.850 --> 00:05:53.540
So thank you again for
having me back this year,

00:05:53.540 --> 00:05:56.320
and think you to Harvard
for hosting this class.

00:05:56.320 --> 00:05:59.120
And then I also have to thank
my assistant Jess, who's

00:05:59.120 --> 00:06:02.475
back there piping lots of
little containers of butter

00:06:02.475 --> 00:06:05.100
cream and caramel sauce, and
little crispy cookies for you guys

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:06.760
to try at the end.

00:06:06.760 --> 00:06:08.040
So there is a tasting.

00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:09.500
[LAUGHING] Yay Jess.

00:06:13.430 --> 00:06:17.020
So, the last two years
that I've taught here,

00:06:17.020 --> 00:06:20.980
I focused very broadly
on just the chemistry

00:06:20.980 --> 00:06:25.600
of science, the chemistry of
baking, science and baking,

00:06:25.600 --> 00:06:28.130
and I focused on making a cake.

00:06:28.130 --> 00:06:31.380
What we did was, we took all
the different ingredients

00:06:31.380 --> 00:06:34.480
that go into a very
simple yellow cake, and I

00:06:34.480 --> 00:06:37.230
talked about emulsification of eggs.

00:06:37.230 --> 00:06:39.092
I talked about gluten formation.

00:06:39.092 --> 00:06:41.050
I talked a little bit
about buttermilk, and how

00:06:41.050 --> 00:06:43.030
it reacts differently than milk.

00:06:43.030 --> 00:06:45.880
I talked about all of the different
ways you can leaven a cake, so

00:06:45.880 --> 00:06:50.700
with air and with steam,
baking soda, baking powder.

00:06:50.700 --> 00:06:55.820
You put all these things together, mix
them all up, and then you get cake.

00:06:55.820 --> 00:06:59.370
And what we did, the
last two years, is we

00:06:59.370 --> 00:07:02.314
taught about the science of
baking through yellow cake.

00:07:02.314 --> 00:07:04.480
These are some examples of
some of the cakes we did,

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:06.610
one with no baking powder,
one with no baking soda,

00:07:06.610 --> 00:07:09.140
we did melted butter instead
of room temperature butter,

00:07:09.140 --> 00:07:10.870
we did a host of different things.

00:07:10.870 --> 00:07:13.750
And it was a super fun lecture to teach.

00:07:13.750 --> 00:07:17.160
Turns out that last year,
two of the students--

00:07:17.160 --> 00:07:19.074
so I teach the class
tonight for the public,

00:07:19.074 --> 00:07:21.990
and then tomorrow I'll come back and
teach to the Harvard students who

00:07:21.990 --> 00:07:25.510
are actually taking this class as
a course-- and two of the students

00:07:25.510 --> 00:07:28.980
last year, upon taking the
science and cooking class,

00:07:28.980 --> 00:07:32.430
and then watching the lecture
that I taught about cake,

00:07:32.430 --> 00:07:35.532
for their final project-- I think
it was their final project-- they

00:07:35.532 --> 00:07:37.240
decided they wanted
to do more with cake,

00:07:37.240 --> 00:07:40.060
and so they came up with spray cake.

00:07:40.060 --> 00:07:43.250
I don't know if any of you guys saw
this, it was actually in The Globe

00:07:43.250 --> 00:07:47.030
about two or three months
ago, it was front page news.

00:07:47.030 --> 00:07:50.410
These two Harvard students
had come up with a cake

00:07:50.410 --> 00:07:53.080
that you can put-- they
put it in an aerosol can.

00:07:53.080 --> 00:07:57.580
It sits on a shelf in the grocery
store, and whenever you're hungry

00:07:57.580 --> 00:08:02.640
and you want cake, you just spray
this into a pan and then bake it.

00:08:02.640 --> 00:08:04.300
And then you get cake.

00:08:04.300 --> 00:08:08.520
So this is for people who think
they cake mixes are too difficult.

00:08:08.520 --> 00:08:12.150
And thus you just want to take
an aerosol can and spray it.

00:08:12.150 --> 00:08:15.180
But they came by the restaurant,
and they baked me some cake,

00:08:15.180 --> 00:08:19.010
they wanted me to approve it,
and see if I thought it was good,

00:08:19.010 --> 00:08:20.780
and I thought it was really good.

00:08:20.780 --> 00:08:23.560
And I have to say it was really
exciting to know that something

00:08:23.560 --> 00:08:26.270
that I had taught had
actually led these students

00:08:26.270 --> 00:08:30.720
and inspired them to create
a product, where they're

00:08:30.720 --> 00:08:32.780
going to go off and make millions.

00:08:32.780 --> 00:08:35.601
So two questions lead
from that, and when

00:08:35.601 --> 00:08:38.559
I told my parents about this-- I sent
it to them because my picture was

00:08:38.559 --> 00:08:40.780
somewhere, and they always
love that kind of stuff--

00:08:40.780 --> 00:08:44.360
the first thing my mom said is,
are you getting royalties on this?

00:08:44.360 --> 00:08:47.030
So that I still don't know,
I haven't heard from them,

00:08:47.030 --> 00:08:51.360
but they might be here in this room,
or maybe they'll watch the video

00:08:51.360 --> 00:08:54.040
and so they know where to fine me.

00:08:54.040 --> 00:08:57.252
You can always tag me along.

00:08:57.252 --> 00:08:58.960
And then the other
question it raises, is

00:08:58.960 --> 00:09:01.270
that it really does up
the ante for this lecture,

00:09:01.270 --> 00:09:06.250
and can I create a lecture that
will inspire people and make people

00:09:06.250 --> 00:09:07.920
innovate something even more exciting?

00:09:07.920 --> 00:09:12.440
So a lot of pressure this time around.

00:09:12.440 --> 00:09:15.580
OK, so this time Professor
Brenner and I talked

00:09:15.580 --> 00:09:21.340
about focusing on a singular subject
rather than the broad topic of cooking

00:09:21.340 --> 00:09:24.790
and baking, and science and chemistry,
but instead on just one subject,

00:09:24.790 --> 00:09:26.150
and that is sugar.

00:09:26.150 --> 00:09:30.410
So this actually came at a great
time when Professor Brenner called me

00:09:30.410 --> 00:09:34.370
last year, because I was just finishing
the manuscript for a new book that

00:09:34.370 --> 00:09:37.450
is coming out next spring-- which
is called Baking With Less Sugar--

00:09:37.450 --> 00:09:42.060
and I just spent the prior year baking
all year long with recipes that I

00:09:42.060 --> 00:09:45.730
was used to using at the bakery, but
with less sugar or with no sugar.

00:09:45.730 --> 00:09:49.790
So I had a lot of experience
baking with less sugar or no sugar,

00:09:49.790 --> 00:09:54.050
and seeing the way the recipes came
out when you didn't have sugar.

00:09:54.050 --> 00:09:56.540
So I was excited to take
everything that I've learned

00:09:56.540 --> 00:09:58.240
and then share that with you guys.

00:09:58.240 --> 00:10:01.450
So you can see all the things you
can make with either no sugar or very

00:10:01.450 --> 00:10:02.420
little sugar.

00:10:02.420 --> 00:10:06.100
It turns out that
sugar is something that

00:10:06.100 --> 00:10:09.240
is genetically engineered inside of us.

00:10:09.240 --> 00:10:13.340
We are all born with
an affinity for sugar,

00:10:13.340 --> 00:10:15.970
and if you have something
sweet in your mouth,

00:10:15.970 --> 00:10:19.140
your body reads it as a
possible source of energy,

00:10:19.140 --> 00:10:22.530
and it reads it as probably not
something that's going to be harmful.

00:10:22.530 --> 00:10:28.150
It doesn't read that when it gets
something sour, or something bitter.

00:10:28.150 --> 00:10:31.460
And so it's having
something that is sweet

00:10:31.460 --> 00:10:36.870
is something that we're all accustomed
to, and that we are all attracted to.

00:10:36.870 --> 00:10:40.980
So when you think about sugar,
and what it does to desserts,

00:10:40.980 --> 00:10:43.570
what is it that defines a dessert?

00:10:43.570 --> 00:10:45.390
Well it's got sugar in it.

00:10:45.390 --> 00:10:48.460
There are very few deserts out
there that don't have sugar.

00:10:48.460 --> 00:10:52.280
You could have a desert that's fresh
fruit, that's what my parents did,

00:10:52.280 --> 00:10:54.510
they thought that was dessert.

00:10:54.510 --> 00:10:57.260
I disagreed.

00:10:57.260 --> 00:11:01.230
Or you can have, some people actually
serve cheese as a last course,

00:11:01.230 --> 00:11:04.620
I don't know some of you guys do
that, I've always found that baffling.

00:11:04.620 --> 00:11:07.870
But this is also another
way people end their meal,

00:11:07.870 --> 00:11:12.110
but really, when we think
about sugar, what we

00:11:12.110 --> 00:11:16.680
think about is all the desserts
that you can create with sugar.

00:11:16.680 --> 00:11:21.130
So, what does sugar do to a desert?

00:11:21.130 --> 00:11:24.380
The most obvious one, if
I were to ask all of you,

00:11:24.380 --> 00:11:27.160
is you would say it adds sweetness.

00:11:27.160 --> 00:11:31.740
It turns out, and Jess and I spent
all afternoon thinking about this,

00:11:31.740 --> 00:11:34.890
finishing up this
presentation, it turns out

00:11:34.890 --> 00:11:38.330
that chocolate is the
only dessert that we

00:11:38.330 --> 00:11:43.040
could think of, in which sugar--
the only role that sugar plays is

00:11:43.040 --> 00:11:44.700
to add sweetness.

00:11:44.700 --> 00:11:47.010
Every other dessert
we came up with there

00:11:47.010 --> 00:11:53.050
was another role that sugar played
in making that dessert palatable.

00:11:53.050 --> 00:11:55.920
So I don't know, I'm going to pose
that as a question to you guys.

00:11:55.920 --> 00:11:57.711
Think about all the
desserts that you know,

00:11:57.711 --> 00:12:01.470
and if you can think of
a desert in which sugar,

00:12:01.470 --> 00:12:04.890
the only role it's playing, is to
make it palatable to your palate,

00:12:04.890 --> 00:12:06.020
to make it sweet.

00:12:06.020 --> 00:12:09.650
Then I would love to hear it,
because we had this blank at first.

00:12:09.650 --> 00:12:11.730
Because we couldn't think
of anything that only

00:12:11.730 --> 00:12:14.620
had sugar to just add sweetness.

00:12:14.620 --> 00:12:19.496
Because sugar plays so many different
roles in every sort of desert.

00:12:19.496 --> 00:12:21.730
Does anybody have any ideas?

00:12:21.730 --> 00:12:23.910
Can anybody think of
any dessert in which

00:12:23.910 --> 00:12:28.980
the only reason you would have
the sugar is to add sweetness?

00:12:28.980 --> 00:12:31.475
The slide that we had, anybody?

00:12:31.475 --> 00:12:31.975
Yes?

00:12:31.975 --> 00:12:33.320
