00:14:38.740 --> 00:14:42.750
So the first thing is creaming
the sugar into butter.

00:14:42.750 --> 00:14:46.510
So any cake recipe,
any cookie recipe, they

00:14:46.510 --> 00:14:50.000
almost all start out with creaming
butter and sugar together.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.960
You take granulated sugar,
you mix it into butter,

00:14:52.960 --> 00:14:56.369
and you cream it, what's
called creaming, in a mixer,

00:14:56.369 --> 00:14:58.910
and you mix it, and mix it, and
mix it until it becomes light

00:14:58.910 --> 00:15:00.170
and fluffy in color.

00:15:00.170 --> 00:15:02.210
And basically what's
happening is, I mean

00:15:02.210 --> 00:15:05.150
you guys all know the texture
of sugar, it's very granulated,

00:15:05.150 --> 00:15:08.800
if you look at those granules
of sugar under a microscope,

00:15:08.800 --> 00:15:10.730
they're little itty bitty crystals.

00:15:10.730 --> 00:15:14.170
And the little sugar crystals
have very hard jagged edges,

00:15:14.170 --> 00:15:19.390
and when they are mixed with the butter,
or margarine, or any sort of solid fat,

00:15:19.390 --> 00:15:24.700
what the sugar crystals are doing,
is they're digging little air

00:15:24.700 --> 00:15:26.910
pockets into the fat.

00:15:26.910 --> 00:15:30.030
So it's sort of like
when you're a gardener,

00:15:30.030 --> 00:15:33.900
and you take a hoe, and your hoeing
the firm earth and you're aerating it.

00:15:33.900 --> 00:15:35.710
And that's exactly what
happens when you're

00:15:35.710 --> 00:15:37.800
creaming sugar and butter together.

00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:40.550
All of those air
pockets then go on, when

00:15:40.550 --> 00:15:44.440
you're making your cake or your cookie,
to make your final product light

00:15:44.440 --> 00:15:47.640
and fluffy and tender,
and not hard and dense.

00:15:47.640 --> 00:15:50.297
So when you think about cookies
and you think about cakes,

00:15:50.297 --> 00:15:52.130
you need the sugar to
make them taste sweet,

00:15:52.130 --> 00:15:55.320
but then you also need them in order
for them to be light and fluffy,

00:15:55.320 --> 00:15:58.260
because of the creaming properties.

00:15:58.260 --> 00:16:01.810
So this is from last
year's lecture, we have

00:16:01.810 --> 00:16:06.510
a picture of a cake in which it's
creamed with a full amount of sugar,

00:16:06.510 --> 00:16:08.450
and then we use half amount of sugar.

00:16:08.450 --> 00:16:10.990
And from the pictures it
doesn't look hugely different,

00:16:10.990 --> 00:16:12.820
but if you were to
imagine a six inch cake,

00:16:12.820 --> 00:16:17.060
there's actually about an inch to a half
an inch all the way through the cake,

00:16:17.060 --> 00:16:19.350
we noticed, when we use
half the amount of sugar.

00:16:19.350 --> 00:16:22.480
And it's because there was half
the amount of sugar crystals

00:16:22.480 --> 00:16:25.540
to create those air pockets,
and so then the final product

00:16:25.540 --> 00:16:29.410
was able to rise quite as much, so
the cake was a little bit denser

00:16:29.410 --> 00:16:32.120
and it didn't rise quite as much.

00:16:32.120 --> 00:16:35.320
Another thing that sugar does
is that it's hygroscopic.

00:16:35.320 --> 00:16:39.940
And what this means, is that it attracts
water molecules that are in the air,

00:16:39.940 --> 00:16:42.090
and it brings it to itself.

00:16:42.090 --> 00:16:47.700
So this is one of the reasons why you
can take cookies, and cakes, and such,

00:16:47.700 --> 00:16:50.040
and you can package them,
and they can sit on the shelf

00:16:50.040 --> 00:16:51.340
and they won't get stale.

00:16:51.340 --> 00:16:53.900
Because with the sugar does,
is it keeps the moisture

00:16:53.900 --> 00:16:56.550
that's already in the
cookie, inside the cookie.

00:16:56.550 --> 00:16:59.860
And it helps it last longer, so
you can put on the supermarket

00:16:59.860 --> 00:17:02.040
and sell it for weeks at a time.

00:17:02.040 --> 00:17:04.690
Originally when we
were talking about what

00:17:04.690 --> 00:17:08.490
is a desert in which the only thing
that sugar does is add sweetness,

00:17:08.490 --> 00:17:10.970
this was the first slide
that I had because I thought,

00:17:10.970 --> 00:17:13.980
well if you take some fruit, and you
mix a little bit of sugar into it,

00:17:13.980 --> 00:17:15.819
and you sweeten it,
then that's a desert,

00:17:15.819 --> 00:17:18.970
and the only thing the sugar is
doing is adding sweetness, right?

00:17:18.970 --> 00:17:20.170
Well it turns out not.

00:17:20.170 --> 00:17:24.240
If you look at the picture closely,
