00:18:13.670 --> 00:18:17.890
But in studying more about the role
of sugar and what it does to desserts,

00:18:17.890 --> 00:18:22.460
sugar actually depresses the
freezing point of a liquid.

00:18:22.460 --> 00:18:26.810
So if we take ice, and we put it in
the freezer, you get an ice cube right?

00:18:26.810 --> 00:18:30.790
It's going to freeze at 0 degrees
Celsius, 32 degrees Fahrenheit.

00:18:30.790 --> 00:18:33.150
If you add some sugar
to that, what it does

00:18:33.150 --> 00:18:38.110
is that it means that that sugar
water won't freeze right at 0 degrees

00:18:38.110 --> 00:18:40.150
Celsius, but it might
be a little bit lower.

00:18:40.150 --> 00:18:44.190
And so if you have a freezer that's at
0 degrees Celsius, then that sugar water

00:18:44.190 --> 00:18:46.040
that you have won't freeze solid.

00:18:46.040 --> 00:18:49.240
So we use this to our advantage
when we're making frozen desserts.

00:18:49.240 --> 00:18:52.137
So when you make a popsicle,
or a sorbet, or milkshake,

00:18:52.137 --> 00:18:54.720
you need the sugar to make it
taste good and to make it sweet,

00:18:54.720 --> 00:18:58.820
but you also need the sugar
to make it actually scoopable,

00:18:58.820 --> 00:19:02.570
so that you can eat it, so it's
not like sucking on an ice cube.

