00:20:29.310 --> 00:20:32.809
OK, so the first thing we're going to
do is just a beat up the egg whites

00:20:32.809 --> 00:20:33.850
without any sugar at all.

00:20:33.850 --> 00:20:39.520
So like I was saying, you have the
protein strands of the egg whites

00:20:39.520 --> 00:20:41.380
are starting to get filled with air.

00:20:41.380 --> 00:20:44.277
And you're going to see-- like this
egg whites before they're beaten,

00:20:44.277 --> 00:20:45.610
they're yellow, they're viscous.

00:20:48.889 --> 00:20:50.680
I think you can start
to see into the bowl,

00:20:50.680 --> 00:20:52.710
you can see how it's starting
to get white and airy,

00:20:52.710 --> 00:20:54.550
that's because all of
the air is starting

00:20:54.550 --> 00:20:57.520
to get captured within the foams.

00:20:57.520 --> 00:21:00.690
Now the protein of the
egg whites, which is now

00:21:00.690 --> 00:21:04.477
capturing all the air, those
protein strands aren't that stable.

00:21:04.477 --> 00:21:06.810
So I'm going to whip this,
and whip this, and whip this,

00:21:06.810 --> 00:21:08.893
and I'm gonna put this out
in the bowl, but you're

00:21:08.893 --> 00:21:11.010
going to see it's going
to be very unstable.

00:21:11.010 --> 00:21:13.290
It's going to look a
little bit like Styrofoam,

00:21:13.290 --> 00:21:15.165
and it's not going to
be anything that you're

00:21:15.165 --> 00:21:18.700
going to be able to really bake with,
because it's going to start to deflate.

00:21:18.700 --> 00:21:23.470
We're going to do another batch
with egg whites and sugar.

00:21:23.470 --> 00:21:27.010
So sugar, when I start to
add that to the egg whites,

00:21:27.010 --> 00:21:31.500
the sugar actually combines with
the water that's in egg whites.

00:21:31.500 --> 00:21:33.800
So egg whites are
protein strands in water.

00:21:33.800 --> 00:21:38.220
We're going to whip up the sugar into
the egg whites, and in that batch,

00:21:38.220 --> 00:21:41.140
the sugar will combine with
the water and it's going

00:21:41.140 --> 00:21:44.050
to create a syrup within this foam.

00:21:44.050 --> 00:21:46.380
And what the syrup is going
to do, is it's actually

00:21:46.380 --> 00:21:49.740
going to protect all of
the little protein bubbles

00:21:49.740 --> 00:21:52.470
that the egg whites are
forming when it goes into foam.

00:21:52.470 --> 00:21:54.430
And so it's sort of
like packing peanuts,

00:21:54.430 --> 00:21:56.210
you know when you have
something fragile,

00:21:56.210 --> 00:21:58.192
you buy all those little
Styrofoam peanuts.

00:21:58.192 --> 00:22:00.650
And you pack your fragile items
and you put lots of peanuts

00:22:00.650 --> 00:22:02.390
around it to make sure it doesn't break.

00:22:02.390 --> 00:22:05.950
That's exactly what will
happen with the sugar.

00:22:05.950 --> 00:22:11.372
So you can see that now the egg
