making, and you're going
to throw butter into it,

00:24:30.931 --> 00:24:32.860
and that's going to be buttercream.

00:24:32.860 --> 00:24:39.430
So those are some things that you
can make with sugar and egg foams.

00:24:39.430 --> 00:24:41.580
So I'm going to let this
go for a little bit,

00:24:41.580 --> 00:24:43.454
and then I'm going to
show you the difference

00:24:43.454 --> 00:24:46.060
between this one and that one.

00:24:46.060 --> 00:24:49.520
So while that's going, I'm going to
give you another thing that sugar does.

00:24:49.520 --> 00:24:52.982
Sugar tenderizes, and
inhibits, gluten development.

00:24:52.982 --> 00:24:55.440
And I'm not going to go into
a big long thing about gluten,

00:24:55.440 --> 00:24:58.675
but basically gluten is a big buzz
word, everybody knows about gluten,

00:24:58.675 --> 00:25:00.450
it means you want to avoid wheat.

00:25:00.450 --> 00:25:04.960
Gluten are two protein molecules
that exist in wheat flour.

00:25:04.960 --> 00:25:07.910
And they exist separately until
you add liquid to wheat flour.

00:25:07.910 --> 00:25:12.170
As soon as you add liquid to it, the
two protein molecules bond together,

00:25:12.170 --> 00:25:15.020
and then they do exactly
what the egg whites do.

00:25:15.020 --> 00:25:19.420
They bond together and they form
these stretchy things that hold air.

00:25:19.420 --> 00:25:22.420
So this is great for
when you have bread.

00:25:22.420 --> 00:25:25.430
If you take bread, which is flour,
water, and a couple other things,

00:25:25.430 --> 00:25:27.900
and you mix it up, you
develop all this gluten,

00:25:27.900 --> 00:25:31.440
and you create a bread that's really
chewy, and it has a lot of great heft,

00:25:31.440 --> 00:25:33.420
and it tastes really great.

00:25:33.420 --> 00:25:35.650
And that's great for bread.

00:25:35.650 --> 00:25:39.640
But when you're making a cake, that's
the last thing in the world you want,

00:25:39.640 --> 00:25:42.530
is a cake that's chewy and not tender.

00:25:42.530 --> 00:25:44.540
You want something
that's light and fluffy.

00:25:44.540 --> 00:25:50.590
What sugar does, similar to what
it does with these egg foams,

00:25:50.590 --> 00:25:55.720
is that the sugar ends up
protecting those two protein gluten

00:25:55.720 --> 00:25:57.840
molecules from bonding.

00:25:57.840 --> 00:26:01.070
And so when you're making a cake batter,
if you have a lot of sugar in it,

00:26:01.070 --> 00:26:03.080
then the sugar's protecting
those from bonding,

00:26:03.080 --> 00:26:04.996
and then you have a cake
that's tender, and it

00:26:04.996 --> 00:26:09.310
doesn't have the ability to hold
all of these big pockets of air,

00:26:09.310 --> 00:26:11.320
which will give you a chewy cake.

00:26:11.320 --> 00:26:13.050
Let me show you this meringue.

00:26:13.050 --> 00:26:14.165
So this is very different.

00:26:18.160 --> 00:26:23.460
So this was the same one cup of--
I'm going to ask my friend here,

00:26:23.460 --> 00:26:25.034
does this look different?

00:26:25.034 --> 00:26:28.444
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:26:28.444 --> 00:26:30.360
JOANNE CHANG: So do you
see how silky that is?

00:26:30.360 --> 00:26:31.416
Where's the camera?

00:26:31.416 --> 00:26:33.320
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:26:33.320 --> 00:26:37.010
JOANNE CHANG: It's like really
silky and much more stable,

00:26:37.010 --> 00:26:40.290
and this is what you would
