00:26:45.182 --> 00:26:46.765
And that's just the addition of sugar.

00:26:57.120 --> 00:26:59.760
Okay, I'm going to start
getting these things going.

00:26:59.760 --> 00:27:00.740
There's that one.

00:27:04.770 --> 00:27:06.710
And then there's that one.

00:27:06.710 --> 00:27:11.570
OK, so a couple more
things, and then we're

00:27:11.570 --> 00:27:13.630
going to start talking
about the stages of sugar.

00:27:13.630 --> 00:27:15.860
So sugar aids in browning.

00:27:15.860 --> 00:27:22.090
So what this means is, at 310 degrees
there are protein molecules and sugars

00:27:22.090 --> 00:27:25.080
that rearrange themselves in
a cake batter, or a cookie,

00:27:25.080 --> 00:27:27.310
or whatever, into these
little ring-- this

00:27:27.310 --> 00:27:31.780
is one of the things I learned, getting
ready for the class-- they rearrange

00:27:31.780 --> 00:27:35.550
themselves into these little ring-like
structures, that then reflect light

00:27:35.550 --> 00:27:38.590
differently to make
something look browner.

00:27:38.590 --> 00:27:42.470
So this is a picture of the sour
cream coffee cake at the bakery.

00:27:42.470 --> 00:27:45.670
So as it turns out, for the
new low sugar baking book,

00:27:45.670 --> 00:27:47.570
I made a sour cream coffee cake.

00:27:47.570 --> 00:27:50.190
This is the exact recipe
that we make at the bakery,

00:27:50.190 --> 00:27:54.359
except it has instead of a full cup of
sugar, it has six tablespoons of sugar.

00:27:54.359 --> 00:27:56.025
And you can see the difference in color.

00:27:56.025 --> 00:27:58.020
I mean there's obviously going
to be a difference in taste,

00:27:58.020 --> 00:28:00.019
but there was such a
drastic difference in color

00:28:00.019 --> 00:28:03.710
that when we took this picture
for the photo shoot, for the book,

00:28:03.710 --> 00:28:07.900
the photographer kept trying
to get me to put it in the oven

00:28:07.900 --> 00:28:10.850
and brown it longer, or he tried
to Photoshop it to make it browner.

00:28:10.850 --> 00:28:13.890
And we knew that this wasn't
a super attractive picture,

00:28:13.890 --> 00:28:16.210
because the one on the left
is what you're typically

00:28:16.210 --> 00:28:19.110
used to seeing when you
think about a beautiful cake.

00:28:19.110 --> 00:28:21.940
But this thing is, that when
you don't have a lot of sugar,

00:28:21.940 --> 00:28:25.290
you're never going to get that browning,
and so we wanted it to be realistic.

00:28:25.290 --> 00:28:27.470
And so this is the picture,
something like this

00:28:27.470 --> 00:28:28.761
is what you'll see in the book.

00:28:28.761 --> 00:28:30.420
Sugar makes pastries crispy.

00:28:30.420 --> 00:28:33.449
And so in something like a
cookie, the sugar will liquefy.

00:28:33.449 --> 00:28:35.490
It's in the cookie batter,
it goes into the oven,

00:28:35.490 --> 00:28:39.130
it liquefies, and then
as the water evaporates,

00:28:39.130 --> 00:28:41.330
the sugar recrystallizes,
and then you end up

00:28:41.330 --> 00:28:43.399
with a cookie that's really crispy.

00:28:43.399 --> 00:28:45.940
So you're going to get a little
bit of a crispy sugar cookie.

00:28:45.940 --> 00:28:48.240
And it's crispy because of the sugar.

00:28:48.240 --> 00:28:52.750
Again, I tried to make a low sugar sugar
cookie for the book, and it was soft.

00:28:52.750 --> 00:28:54.750
It wasn't that sweet, but
it was also just soft,

00:28:54.750 --> 00:28:57.100
and there was no way we
can get it to crisp up.

00:28:57.100 --> 00:28:59.150
We ended up doing a ginger
snap, and what we did

00:28:59.150 --> 00:29:01.360
was rather than-- because
it wouldn't crisp up,

00:29:01.360 --> 00:29:04.650
because it didn't have any sugar in
it, we put it in an oven overnight

00:29:04.650 --> 00:29:05.900
and we dried it out.

00:29:05.900 --> 00:29:09.094
And then it ended up just
being a hard dehydrated cookie.

00:29:09.094 --> 00:29:10.135
So it was sort of crispy.

00:29:10.135 --> 00:29:10.470
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:29:10.470 --> 00:29:13.094
JOANNE CHANG: I know that sounds
really appetizing, doesn't it?

00:29:13.094 --> 00:29:14.560
No, it's really good.

00:29:14.560 --> 00:29:21.370
And then finally, sugar caramelizes
between 356 degrees and 390 degrees,

00:29:21.370 --> 00:29:23.600
sugar will caramelize.

00:29:23.600 --> 00:29:27.170
And that adds to the flavor of a
cookie, or cake, or tart shell,

00:29:27.170 --> 00:29:31.630
you get that really nice
toasty, nutty aroma.

00:29:31.630 --> 00:29:37.340
OK, so the next thing we're going to
talk about is the stages of sugar.

00:29:37.340 --> 00:29:39.320
I'm going to come back
and babysit these guys.

00:29:39.320 --> 00:29:47.690
So when you take sugar and
water and make it into a syrup,

00:29:47.690 --> 00:29:51.110
and you boil it at the
various temperatures

00:29:51.110 --> 00:30:01.540
that you boil the sugar water
to, it corresponds to the way

00:30:01.540 --> 00:30:06.210
the sugar reacts in cold water.

00:30:06.210 --> 00:30:09.950
And so the first stage is thread stage.

00:30:09.950 --> 00:30:12.200
This is the easy one, you just boil it.

00:30:12.200 --> 00:30:15.550
At 230 degrees to 235 degrees,
it's called thread stage.

00:30:15.550 --> 00:30:19.290
If you pour a little bit of this into
some water, you'll get little threads

00:30:19.290 --> 00:30:20.710
and then it goes to the bottom.

00:30:20.710 --> 00:30:24.850
This is used for sweetening iced
tea, or just glazing fruits.

00:30:24.850 --> 00:30:27.905
The second stage is soft ball.

00:30:27.905 --> 00:30:32.650
At soft ball, which is what I'm
taking this to, you can make fudge.

00:30:32.650 --> 00:30:37.340
I'm going to take my between soft ball
and the next one, which is firm ball.

00:30:37.340 --> 00:30:40.280
So at firm ball, you can make caramels.

00:30:40.280 --> 00:30:43.097
So these are the
difference in temperatures.

00:30:43.097 --> 00:30:44.180
I'm going to go backwards.

00:30:44.180 --> 00:30:48.790
So if you look at soft ball, 235 to
240, when you take the sugar water

00:30:48.790 --> 00:30:51.350
and you put it in cold water,
you'll get a soft ball.

00:30:51.350 --> 00:30:53.940
That's how it got its name, and
then with firm ball, when you

00:30:53.940 --> 00:30:55.440
do the same thing you get a firm ball.

00:30:55.440 --> 00:30:57.690
And that's how, so you don't
need a candy thermometer,

00:30:57.690 --> 00:30:59.350
because you can just use your hands.

00:30:59.350 --> 00:31:01.290
But the thing is, is
that it's really hot.

00:31:01.290 --> 00:31:04.890
So you have to first
freeze your fingers.

00:31:04.890 --> 00:31:06.700
And the other thing
that you can do-- and I

00:31:06.700 --> 00:31:08.825
don't know if you can hear
it because I'm talking--

00:31:08.825 --> 00:31:13.530
but when you hear sugar water boil,
it just sounds like water at first.

00:31:13.530 --> 00:31:18.850
And then, as it starts to get more and
more concentrated, you can hear it,

00:31:18.850 --> 00:31:20.929
and it starts to thicken.

00:31:20.929 --> 00:31:22.720
And when it gets to
the right temperature--

00:31:22.720 --> 00:31:24.690
and this is only because I've
been doing it for years--

00:31:24.690 --> 00:31:27.500
you can actually tell when it's
hitting about soft ball stage.

00:31:27.500 --> 00:31:30.208
So that way you don't have to
plunge your finger in all the time,

00:31:30.208 --> 00:31:31.859
you can wait.

00:31:31.859 --> 00:31:32.650
So can you hear it?

00:31:32.650 --> 00:31:34.720
It's a little bit slower now.

00:31:34.720 --> 00:31:43.400
So now I'm going to take a little bit,
and now I've gone a little bit too far.

00:31:43.400 --> 00:31:47.370
No here we go, firm ball.

00:31:47.370 --> 00:31:50.800
You can't really see that, but
there's a firm little ball.

00:31:50.800 --> 00:31:53.995
OK, now we're going to make meringue.

00:31:58.920 --> 00:32:05.780
So this is very similar
to the meringue that we

00:32:05.780 --> 00:32:08.070
made that's sitting
over there in that bowl,

00:32:08.070 --> 00:32:10.230
except that I've cooked the sugar.

00:32:10.230 --> 00:32:14.170
This will help make it--
that meringue, is not

00:32:14.170 --> 00:32:16.120
quite as stable as this meringue.

00:32:30.600 --> 00:32:36.945
So I've just taken that sugar syrup,
and I've poured it into the egg whites.

00:32:41.960 --> 00:32:46.110
I'm going to take this Italian meringue,
and I'm going to throw butter into it,

00:32:46.110 --> 00:32:47.412
and then that's buttercream.

00:32:47.412 --> 00:32:50.620
And that's what you use to frost a cake,
and that's what you're going to eat,

00:32:50.620 --> 00:32:53.570
is a little bit of butter cream.

00:32:53.570 --> 00:32:56.570
OK, but you have to wait until this
cools before you can add the butter.

00:32:56.570 --> 00:32:59.130
So while that's cooling,

00:32:59.130 --> 00:33:02.620
I'm going to go back to
this slide really quick.

00:33:02.620 --> 00:33:08.310
Hard ball is what you
use to make marshmallows.

00:33:08.310 --> 00:33:12.480
And then soft crack, is taffy.

00:33:12.480 --> 00:33:15.040
Hard crack is lollipops.

00:33:15.040 --> 00:33:18.800
And then the final
stage, is caramelization.

00:33:18.800 --> 00:33:22.440
And that's when you take the sugar
so far that it starts to turn tan,

00:33:22.440 --> 00:33:24.150
and then it starts to
turn brown, and you

00:33:24.150 --> 00:33:28.819
can make praline, and caramel sauce,
and a whole bunch of other things.

00:33:28.819 --> 00:33:29.860
So does that makes sense?

00:33:29.860 --> 00:33:34.158
All of the stages of sugar, and
why they have the different names?

00:33:34.158 --> 00:33:34.657
OK.

00:33:37.640 --> 00:33:39.780
Because you can definitely
use a candy thermometer,

00:33:39.780 --> 00:33:43.220
but if you know what you're
looking for, you don't have to,

00:33:43.220 --> 00:33:44.800
and you can just use ice water.

00:33:44.800 --> 00:33:47.340
And then you'll know
exactly how far to take it.

00:33:47.340 --> 00:33:50.505
OK, so let's revisit these meringues.

00:33:54.930 --> 00:33:58.250
You can see this one.

00:33:58.250 --> 00:34:03.380
So can you see, this is the one that
was just egg white, and no sugar.

00:34:03.380 --> 00:34:06.195
And it's basically just deflating
in front of our very eyes.

00:34:06.195 --> 00:34:09.500
It's very sad.

00:34:09.500 --> 00:34:10.550
Useless.

00:34:10.550 --> 00:34:14.260
This has been stabilized with sugar.

00:34:14.260 --> 00:34:18.470
So you can see it's still beautiful,
you can make cookies out of this.

00:34:18.470 --> 00:34:21.949
You could fold almond flour,
and make French macaroon,

00:34:21.949 --> 00:34:25.050
that's what you'd use this for.

00:34:25.050 --> 00:34:28.310
The Italian one, which is over there,
we're going to wait until it cools,

00:34:28.310 --> 00:34:34.420
and then this one we are
going to make praline.

00:34:34.420 --> 00:34:39.150
Praline is when you take sugar,
and you wait until it caramelizes.

00:34:39.150 --> 00:34:44.570
So right now it's reaching
about firm ball, hard ball,

00:34:44.570 --> 00:34:49.305
because it's really,
really slow in its bubbles.

00:34:49.305 --> 00:34:57.340
And the bubbles are getting
really big, they're very slow.

00:34:57.340 --> 00:35:00.450
And now it'll slowly
start to turn color.

00:35:00.450 --> 00:35:03.930
And as soon as it starts to
caramelize, to make praline

00:35:03.930 --> 00:35:07.845
you just pour nuts into it, then
pour it out onto a sheet tray,

00:35:07.845 --> 00:35:08.720
and then let it cool.

00:35:17.820 --> 00:35:22.740
OK, so while that one is
waiting to caramelize,

00:35:22.740 --> 00:35:24.490
we're going to add the
butter to this one.

00:35:24.490 --> 00:35:27.700
Sorry, I don't mean
to keep moving around.

00:35:27.700 --> 00:35:30.127
Can you see how much this has grown?

00:35:30.127 --> 00:35:31.710
I don't know if you guys can see that.

00:35:31.710 --> 00:35:36.700
So to make butter cream, you just take
the butter and you just throw it in.

00:35:36.700 --> 00:35:39.620
It's got to be soft butter,
it can't be too cold

00:35:39.620 --> 00:35:41.455
or it'll shock the whole thing.

00:35:41.455 --> 00:35:48.280
But it can't be melted butter, because
then it won't be stable enough.

00:35:48.280 --> 00:36:00.710
And it's about a cup of egg whites, a
cup of sugar, and a pound of butter.

00:36:06.590 --> 00:36:09.084
Does that sound like a lot?

00:36:09.084 --> 00:36:10.750
I feel like this is such a small amount.

00:36:10.750 --> 00:36:11.830
Like, I'm almost done.

00:36:14.850 --> 00:36:18.750
And what will happen is, as the butter
will slowly mix into the meringue,

00:36:18.750 --> 00:36:22.220
and it's going to look broken at first,
it's going to look like we messed up,

00:36:22.220 --> 00:36:27.330
and then slowly it'll all come
together and we'll have buttercream.

00:36:27.330 --> 00:36:31.320
OK, so that one is working.

00:36:31.320 --> 00:36:33.890
And now, we're going to come back here.

00:36:33.890 --> 00:36:35.590
And now you can see, you see that?

00:36:35.590 --> 00:36:38.370
How nice that looks?

00:36:38.370 --> 00:36:49.690
So I'm just going to swirl this
around a little bit, and add my nuts,

00:36:49.690 --> 00:36:51.170
swirl to coat.

00:37:09.070 --> 00:37:14.900
And probably about 10 or 15 minutes
will cool, and it'll be really hard,

00:37:14.900 --> 00:37:18.650
and then you can break it off
and some people can eat it.

00:37:18.650 --> 00:37:21.190
Because we only have this much.

00:37:21.190 --> 00:37:22.740
So we'll put it right there.

00:37:22.740 --> 00:37:24.840
We're going to make caramel
sauce, and then we're

00:37:24.840 --> 00:37:29.270
going to finish with croquembouche.

00:37:29.270 --> 00:37:33.870
Which is the picture that the
beginning of the slide show began with.

00:37:41.740 --> 00:37:44.895
So right now I'm just adding
water to the sugar to dissolve it.

00:37:51.390 --> 00:37:54.230
And then we're going to take
it just as far as we took that.

00:38:00.780 --> 00:38:03.650
And this one we're waiting
to get a little bit

00:38:03.650 --> 00:38:05.990
brown so that we can make caramel sauce.

00:38:05.990 --> 00:38:08.697
OK, so here we go, we're going
to look at the butter cream.

00:38:35.038 --> 00:38:37.577
And so this is buttercream.

00:38:37.577 --> 00:38:39.535
And this is what you
would use to frost a cake.

00:38:43.949 --> 00:38:45.990
So if you want, you can
make this ahead of time--

00:38:45.990 --> 00:38:48.790
I know this isn't a baking class--
but just so you know, if you want,

00:38:48.790 --> 00:38:51.123
you can make this ahead of
time, store it in the fridge,

00:38:51.123 --> 00:38:53.950
and then when you want to reuse
