Where it says 85% sugar,
what else is in the mixture?

00:40:05.440 --> 00:40:06.120
Water.

00:40:06.120 --> 00:40:08.340
And so the reason that the
textures are so different

00:40:08.340 --> 00:40:11.700
is because you know if it's all
sugar, it'll be really hard.

00:40:11.700 --> 00:40:17.581
But see at 95% sugar then the
texture is softer, 92% it's softer.

00:40:17.581 --> 00:40:19.330
so what you're really
doing is controlling

00:40:19.330 --> 00:40:22.460
the water content, of the mixture.

00:40:22.460 --> 00:40:26.100
JOANNE CHANG: So, we're going
to now make caramel sauce.

00:40:26.100 --> 00:40:28.882
So you can see, that it's
now nice and caramelized.

00:40:28.882 --> 00:40:31.090
And one trick-- again I know
it's not a baking class,

00:40:31.090 --> 00:40:34.214
but just in case you guys decide to
make something-- when you make caramel,

00:40:34.214 --> 00:40:38.160
right now it looks really brown, but
the real key is, what you want to do

00:40:38.160 --> 00:40:43.670
is, actually tilt the pan,
and then look at what results.

00:40:43.670 --> 00:40:44.920
Because that's the true color.

00:40:44.920 --> 00:40:48.770
So I think a lot of bakers, they
think, oh, this is caramel, I'm done.

00:40:48.770 --> 00:40:50.350
But no, this isn't dark enough.

00:40:50.350 --> 00:40:53.090
What you want to do is take
it, tilt it, and then look

00:40:53.090 --> 00:40:57.910
and then that fine
sheen is the true color.

00:40:57.910 --> 00:41:00.137
OK, now it's good.

00:41:00.137 --> 00:41:02.970
And then we're going to add cream,
but you have to be really careful

00:41:02.970 --> 00:41:08.900
because it's-- and that's caramel sauce.

00:41:11.570 --> 00:41:14.959
And then this one, this
is the last one, which

00:41:14.959 --> 00:41:17.000
is, I'm going to do what's
called spinning sugar.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:20.200
And that's taking caramel,
and then creating--

00:41:20.200 --> 00:41:22.380
because remember how we
talked about soft ball,

00:41:22.380 --> 00:41:26.310
firm ball, hard ball, soft crack, hard
crack-- it turns out at hard crack

00:41:26.310 --> 00:41:29.820
and beyond, what that means
is that when the sugar cools,

00:41:29.820 --> 00:41:31.620
it becomes like a crack.

00:41:31.620 --> 00:41:32.860
It cracks.

00:41:32.860 --> 00:41:39.070
And caramel, which is way past hard
crack, when you flick it really fast,

00:41:39.070 --> 00:41:44.140
it creates these long sugar strands
that end up looking very beautiful,

00:41:44.140 --> 00:41:46.430
and that's spun sugar.

00:41:46.430 --> 00:41:49.329
And last year when I did
it, I had a pot of sugar

00:41:49.329 --> 00:41:52.620
and it crystallized in the middle of the
lecture, and I was like, what do I do?

00:41:52.620 --> 00:41:56.220
So crystallization of sugar is when
you're doing what we've been doing,

00:41:56.220 --> 00:41:58.640
you put sugar and water in
a pot and you turn it on,

00:41:58.640 --> 00:42:02.160
you think you're making either
softball for a butter cream

00:42:02.160 --> 00:42:04.762
or you're making caramel for
caramel sauce, and you come

00:42:04.762 --> 00:42:06.470
and you look at it,
and all of a sudden--

00:42:06.470 --> 00:42:08.760
and I was actually worried
that that might happen tonight,

00:42:08.760 --> 00:42:11.760
but I probably should have let it
happen so that I could show you guys.

00:42:11.760 --> 00:42:13.468
So when you come back
and you look at it,

00:42:13.468 --> 00:42:16.570
it turns out it starts to have-- I
don't even know how to describe it,

00:42:16.570 --> 00:42:21.510
it kind of looks like pieces of
ice floating in the sugar syrup.

00:42:21.510 --> 00:42:24.140
So everything that you've
seen, has been perfect.

00:42:24.140 --> 00:42:26.280
Everything's boiled,
this look so perfect.

00:42:26.280 --> 00:42:28.300
It's just boiling and boiling.

00:42:28.300 --> 00:42:32.160
But it turns out, there's a couple
things that cause crystallisation.

00:42:32.160 --> 00:42:34.230
That I know of, from a
pastry point of view.

00:42:34.230 --> 00:42:37.800
I don't really know what it means
from a scientific point of view.

00:42:37.800 --> 00:42:43.410
But if you have any sugar crystals
that are on the side of the pan.

00:42:43.410 --> 00:42:46.800
So when you take sugar and
water and you mix them together,

00:42:46.800 --> 00:42:49.220
you don't want to splash
sugar crystals on the side.

00:42:49.220 --> 00:42:51.380
You may have noticed that
when I put the water in,

00:42:51.380 --> 00:42:52.713
I didn't just pour the water in.

00:42:52.713 --> 00:42:56.820
I very gently put the water in, I really
gently moved the sugar to dissolve it.

00:42:56.820 --> 00:42:59.160
Because if there's any sugar
crystals on the side, then

00:42:59.160 --> 00:43:02.890
there's a chance that those sugar
crystals, they're very influential.

00:43:02.890 --> 00:43:05.200
And when this is happening,
it's at this point when

00:43:05.200 --> 00:43:07.840
it starts to go into soft
ball, firm ball stage,

00:43:07.840 --> 00:43:12.200
but if there's a sugar crystal, the
sugar crystal will fall into the syrup

00:43:12.200 --> 00:43:15.450
and it'll just cause this chain
reaction that will then cause

00:43:15.450 --> 00:43:19.970
what looks like ice on the top of it.

00:43:19.970 --> 00:43:22.490
And it can happen at any stage.

00:43:22.490 --> 00:43:25.535
The other times it
happens is if you move it.

00:43:25.535 --> 00:43:27.910
So I don't know if you've
noticed, but I won't touch this

00:43:27.910 --> 00:43:29.410
until it starts to caramelize.

00:43:29.410 --> 00:43:34.160
So if you move the sugar syrup while
it's boiling, it for some reason

00:43:34.160 --> 00:43:36.974
jostles it and makes
it want to crystallize.

00:43:36.974 --> 00:43:38.140
And so those are two tricks.

00:43:38.140 --> 00:43:41.410
You want to make sure that there's
no sugar on the edge of the pan,

00:43:41.410 --> 00:43:44.010
and then you don't want to
touch it until it caramelizes.

00:43:44.010 --> 00:43:46.300
As soon as it caramelizes,
you can touch it.

00:43:46.300 --> 00:43:49.050
And you can swirl it around,
and even out the caramelization.

00:43:49.050 --> 00:43:53.430
But before then if you touch it,
there's a chance it will crystallize.

00:43:53.430 --> 00:43:56.930
Some things that you can do, you
can try to just boil it gently,

00:43:56.930 --> 00:43:58.880
and sometimes it boils away.

00:43:58.880 --> 00:44:01.070
But a lot of times you
just have to start over.

00:44:01.070 --> 00:44:02.550
And so like during the
holidays when we're

00:44:02.550 --> 00:44:04.466
making millions and
millions of croquembouche,

00:44:04.466 --> 00:44:07.070
we have pots of sugar
just going on every stove

00:44:07.070 --> 00:44:10.299
because one out of every
ten ends up crystallizing,

00:44:10.299 --> 00:44:11.340
and then we can't use it.

00:44:11.340 --> 00:44:13.440
So we always have these backup pots.

00:44:13.440 --> 00:44:13.870
MICHAEL BRENNER: Is that?

00:44:13.870 --> 00:44:14.370
How's that?

00:44:14.370 --> 00:44:16.760
JOANNE CHANG: Yeah, I think
let's do this for a sec.

00:44:16.760 --> 00:44:20.930
So the sugar actually started to
crystallize, which is too bad.

00:44:20.930 --> 00:44:23.240
OK, so now you can see,
so this is caramel right?

00:44:23.240 --> 00:44:26.510
We've made it, and we let it sit,
and now it's starting to cool down.

00:44:26.510 --> 00:44:29.410
And as it cools, it thickens up.

00:44:29.410 --> 00:44:32.050
And then-- so what I'm
doing is, I keep lifting

00:44:32.050 --> 00:44:36.880
it to see if it'll just fall in one
continuous strand without breaking.

00:44:36.880 --> 00:44:39.380
And then once I feel like
it's a nice thick layer--

00:44:39.380 --> 00:44:42.890
I'm going to try not to make
too much of a mass here.

00:44:42.890 --> 00:44:45.840
So then what you can do is just
do what's called spun sugar.

00:44:45.840 --> 00:44:49.494
Which is you basically--

00:44:54.840 --> 00:44:57.610
So I let a lot of it drip off,
because I don't want clumps of it,

00:44:57.610 --> 00:44:59.300
and then I just flick.

00:44:59.300 --> 00:45:02.300
And you can see that
it just starts to fall,

00:45:02.300 --> 00:45:06.050
because it's past that soft crack stage.

00:45:06.050 --> 00:45:08.720
I mean there's a lot of
different ways you can do this,

00:45:08.720 --> 00:45:11.490
and typically you should do
this on a piece of parchment,

00:45:11.490 --> 00:45:14.470
it makes cleanup a little bit easier.

00:45:14.470 --> 00:45:17.640
I'll do that tomorrow, I forgot, sorry.

00:45:17.640 --> 00:45:19.590
OK, and then so this is
just the start of it.

00:45:19.590 --> 00:45:26.140
So then you can take all of this
spun sugar and just wrap it around.

00:45:26.140 --> 00:45:31.450
Here, I'll go this way so
that-- but it's super easy.

00:45:31.450 --> 00:45:34.200
You just hold this, and then you flick.

00:45:34.200 --> 00:45:35.740
So you have to flick.

00:45:35.740 --> 00:45:38.720
It's a really quick, quick flicking.

00:45:44.140 --> 00:45:47.240
So a lot of times people do this,
I'm going to show you what not to do.

00:45:47.240 --> 00:45:51.990
So a lot of times
people will do this, OK.

00:45:51.990 --> 00:45:57.140
But what you want to do is,
again let a lot of it runoff,

00:45:57.140 --> 00:46:04.450
and then just flick really fast.

00:46:04.450 --> 00:46:10.010
And then as the sugar
falls from the utensil,

00:46:10.010 --> 00:46:15.110
it'll form these strands
that then become spun sugar.

00:46:15.110 --> 00:46:19.240
And so then as this gets
colder, it becomes harder

00:46:19.240 --> 00:46:24.410
to spin because the sugar gets
more and more firm and hard.

00:46:24.410 --> 00:46:27.074
And then you can do what's
called pulled sugar.

00:46:27.074 --> 00:46:29.740
Actually, you would never take
it to caramel to do pulled sugar,

00:46:29.740 --> 00:46:34.930
but if you take sugar to hard
crack stage and then let it cool,

00:46:34.930 --> 00:46:39.949
it becomes stiffer as it cools.

00:46:39.949 --> 00:46:42.240
And as it becomes stiffer,
you can start to lift it up,

00:46:42.240 --> 00:46:44.890
and it starts to feel like
caramel, and you start to pull it.

00:46:44.890 --> 00:46:48.110
And that's how they make all those
beautiful flowers, and birds,

00:46:48.110 --> 00:46:52.160
and butterflies, and stuff like that.

00:46:52.160 --> 00:46:55.700
So this is, you just keep going
until you cover it, and as

00:46:55.700 --> 00:46:57.490
much caramel as you want.

00:46:57.490 --> 00:47:00.054
The tricky thing about
croquembouche, and about spun sugar,

00:47:00.054 --> 00:47:01.720
is that it's very temperature dependent.

00:47:01.720 --> 00:47:03.410
And it's very humidity dependent.

00:47:03.410 --> 00:47:05.340
And so you actually
can make it, and it'll

00:47:05.340 --> 00:47:09.200
last for about an hour or two hours,
and then it just starts to melt.

00:47:09.200 --> 00:47:11.910
And if it's raining outside,
you don't even have that long.

00:47:11.910 --> 00:47:14.762
You probably have like 15 minutes,
and then it just starts to melt.

00:47:14.762 --> 00:47:16.720
MICHAEL BRENNER: Can I
ask you guys a question?

00:47:16.720 --> 00:47:19.259
So why do you have to flick it?

00:47:19.259 --> 00:47:19.800
Anybody know?

00:47:25.160 --> 00:47:28.360
It has to, it has to hit air.

00:47:28.360 --> 00:47:30.610
So somebody said cool
rapidly, so when you flick it,

00:47:30.610 --> 00:47:34.610
I think you evaporate the liquid out
faster, and it solidifies faster.

00:47:34.610 --> 00:47:36.840
If you go like this,
it doesn't evaporate,

00:47:36.840 --> 00:47:41.720
so probably it's liquid when it
comes down if you don't flick it.

00:47:41.720 --> 00:47:45.470
JOANNE CHANG: I think because as
it cools-- so if I just take it,

00:47:45.470 --> 00:47:48.679
and just move it--

00:47:48.679 --> 00:47:50.220
MICHAEL BRENNER: You're just pouring.

00:47:50.220 --> 00:47:51.610
JOANNE CHANG: Yeah,
then it's just pouring.

00:47:51.610 --> 00:47:53.300
So it's not really, it's like--

00:47:53.300 --> 00:47:54.110
MICHAEL BRENNER: When
you move something,

00:47:54.110 --> 00:47:55.700
so there's this wonderful
experiment that we've

00:47:55.700 --> 00:47:57.699
all don, that if you blow
on a spoon that's hot,

00:47:57.699 --> 00:48:01.889
it cools faster, then if you let
it-- And that's because evaporated,

00:48:01.889 --> 00:48:03.180
you carry the heat away faster.

00:48:03.180 --> 00:48:05.380
Sort of evaporates faster.

00:48:05.380 --> 00:48:08.030
So should we-- I think we
should take more questions.

00:48:08.030 --> 00:48:09.570
Let me propose several things.

